<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2102EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique-Zimbabwe     04-01 0196</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Mozambique-Zimbabwe,0200</SECOND><HEAD>Zimbabweans Aid Mozambique Forces In Guerrilla Raids</HEAD><DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Zimbabwean forces joined Mozambicansoldiers in attacks that destroyed three major guerrilla bases insouthern Mozambique this month, the army announced Friday.   The national news agency, AIM, said it was the firstconfirmation of Zimbabwean participation in the 12-year-old civilwar between Marxist government forces and the Mozambique NationalResistance, which the government says is South African-backed.   Zimbabwean forces have been in neighboring Mozambique forseveral years, helping to guard the Limpopo Railway line which runsfor over 300 miles from the border to the port of Maputo.   Zimbabwean and Mozambican railway workers are repairing thetrack, which will give Zimbabwe a second outlet to the sea. Theother line, to the port of Beira, functions well, said AIM. It alsois guarded by Zimbabweans.   AIM quoted a spokesman for the general staff of the Mozambicanarmed forces as saying the joint force attacked the bases ofChiconjo, Maginge and Nhahombe in Gaza province during the secondhalf of March, killing 260 bandits.   There have been several reports of Mozambican guerrillas raidingvillages in Zimbabwe since that country sent troops into Mozambique.</TEXT></DOC>